<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900411-0064</DOCNO><DOCID>900411-0064.</DOCID><HL>   South Africa's Vehicle Sales</HL><DATE>04/11/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   AFRIC</CO><IN>AUTOMOBILES (AUT)</IN><LP>   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa -- South African new vehiclesales in March declined 5.0%, to 30,577 units, from 32,183units a year earlier, the National Association of AutomobileManufacturers said.   March sales were 9.8% higher than the 27,860 units sold inFebruary, the association said.</LP><TEXT>   NAAMSA's director, Nico Vermeulen, said seasonal factorsand a slightly improved manufacturers' supply position hadcontributed to a modest improvement in new car and lightcommercial-vehicle sales. However, he added that officialmeasures to cool off the economy continued to have a negativeimpact on new car sales, and current difficult marketconditions were expected to persist into the second half of1990. But sales of new motor vehicles were expected toimprove gradually, provided interest rates declined duringthe latter part of the year.   March sales of passenger vehicles of 19,043 units were7.0% lower than the 20,477 units sold a year earlier, but13.4% higher than February sales of 16,799 units.   Commercial-vehicle sales for March totaled 11,534 units,1.5% higher than 11,706 units sold a year earlier and 4.3% upfrom February's 11,061 units.   Vehicle sales for the first three months of the yeartotaled 84,872 units, down 1.7% from 86,348 units sold in thesame period of 1989.</TEXT></DOC>